            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/>Μαγούλια Σπὴς
                    <lb n="2"/>χρηστὰ καὶ ἄμε
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/><hi rend="small">ν</hi>πτος ἔζησεν ἔτη
                    <lb n="4"/><space quantity="4" unit="character"/>∙ ο ∙<space quantity="7" unit="character" precision="medium"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <p></p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it">
                <p>Magulia Spes, buona e senza macchia, visse 70 anni</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <p>Magulia Spes, good and blameless, has lived for 80 years</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The first name of the deceased has been read as Μαγούνα by Keibel and integrated as Μαγούλνια by Franz, but there are no paralles for such names. Conversely, Ferrua has proposed Μαγούλια, which has a well-established comparison with lat. gentilicium Magullius. This Latinism would be consistent with the name "Spes", which appears also in another inscription from Syracuse (I.Sicily 0865). According to Korhonen 2004 (and cf. Solin 1997 pp. 2-3), "Il quadro cronologico delle attestazioni del cognome Spes si estende dalla prima età imperiale alla fine del IV o inizi del V secolo", and the period between the 1st and the 4th c. BC is suitable for I.Sicily 0859 as well.
                    <!--Magoulnia Spes; chrestos kai amemptos; age in yrs.--></p>
            </div>
